<div class="article_title">
<h2 class="heading-1"><span id="H5BWeb20audiencemeasurementdemonstration3Ehttp3A2F2Fwwwalentycom2Fxwiki2Fbin2Fview2FDemo2FAudienceDemo3Flanguage3Den5D"><span class="wikiexternallink"><a href="http://www.alenty.com/xwiki/bin/view/Demo/AudienceDemo?language=en">Web 2.0 audience measurement demonstration</a></span></span></h2><p class="paragraph"/>
</div>
The purpose of this page is to demonstrate how we measure the audience of a web 2.0 site.<p class="paragraph"/>
As a reminder,  a web 2.0 site has one of the following  two following characteristics:
<ul class="star">
<li>visitors share information</li>
<li>the content of a page is refreshed piece  by piece (Ajax technologies)</li>
</ul>This page has both characteristics.
<h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HHowtousethisexample3F">How to use this example?</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

At the bottom right corner of the page, a green rectangle is displayed,  and continuously updated.
It illustrate the information that our script records.<p class="paragraph"/>
The frequency of updates is higher than on a normal site, so that you can visualize the dynamic aspect of our measurement system.
<h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HTimemeasurement">Time measurement</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

Time spent is the most important indicator of web 2.0. It replaces page views, which became meaningless when pages are refreshed piece by piece (Ajax)<p class="paragraph"/>
Time is only taken into account when the script detects mouse-keyboard activity on the page.  Time count is stopped ofter a certain idle time. In this demonstration, time is "stopped" after 10 seconds of idle time. In a normal configuration, the idle time is more important: one minute for instance for a "text" site, without video.<p class="paragraph"/>
Time is only taken into account when the script detects mouse-keyboard activity on the page. Time count is stopped after a certain idle time. In this demonstration, time is "stopped" after 10 seconds of idle time. In a normal configuration, the idle time is more important: one minute for instance for a "text" site, without video.<p class="paragraph"/>
Stop to move your mouse (and don't touch your keyboard) during 10 seconds. The windows in the lower right corner does not refresh anymore!
<h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HVisibilitymeasurement">Visibility measurement</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

Content visibility is also used to measure time. As soon as a content is not visible anymore, our script stops counting is time of display.<p class="paragraph"/>
You can make the following experiment:
<ul class="star">
<li>check the total time of the page (last line in the green rectangle)</li>
<li>switch to another application, or another tab on your navigator</li>
<li>count 10 seconds (this page must no longer be visible)</li>
<li>come back on this page and look at the total time: it did not change!</li>
</ul><h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HContentmeasurement">Content measurement</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

The demo rectangle shows the different contents that belong to the page. The url <span class="nobr"><a href="http://www.alenty.com/xwiki/bin/view/Demo/AudienceDemo">http://www.alenty.com/xwiki/bin/view/Demo/AudienceDemo</a></span> corresponds to the article that you are currently reading, without the comments, which are considered as different contents. The comments are identified by their numbers (comment0, comment1, etc.).<p class="paragraph"/>
Every second, our script knows if these comments are visible, and what their visible surface is. This allows us to know if and how long a comment has been seen by a visitor.<p class="paragraph"/>
There are many usage for this measurement:
<ul class="star">
<li>know if a banner has been seen</li>
<li>measure how long each product is seen in a search page</li>
<li>measure the fact that an article is read on the Home page of a blog (where, every day, the last articles are included)...</li>
</ul>Scroll up and down this page and you will see the information of the visibility of the different contents will be updated!
<h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HDynamicdisplays28Ajax29">Dynamic displays (Ajax)</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

Who's hot widget filtering is a typical Ajax functionality. When you move the cursor on the thermometer, comments are filtered according to the temperature of their author.<p class="paragraph"/>
You will notice that the demo rectangle takes into account the comment filtering.
<h3 class="heading-1-1"><span id="HAgenericscriptforallweb20sites">A generic script for all web 2.0 sites</span></h3><p class="paragraph"/>

This demo is a genuine one, using the very same script as the one you can have in your web 2.0 site!<p class="paragraph"/>
All kinds of configurations are possible, <span class="wikilink"><a href="/xwiki/bin/view/Main/Contact">contact us</a></span> to measure your web 2.0 site efficiently, at last!<p class="paragraph"/>
Check out our other demos:
<ul class="star">
<li><span class="wikilink"><a href="/xwiki/bin/view/Demo/AudienceDemoMultiContent">Displaying multiplpe contents in multiple locations</a></span></li>
<li><span class="wikilink"><a href="/xwiki/bin/view/Demo/BannerExposure?language=en">Banner visiblity measurement</a></span></li>
</ul></div>
